report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 48-year-old woman with seizures since childhood, seizure-free for years and then recurrent seizures for the last two years.  Convulsions yesterday.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Lipitor.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  There are spontaneous arousals from drowsiness and then she drifts off to a drowsy pattern with slow rolling eye movements and a beta background.  Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and produces some head rocking artifact.  The head rocking artifact is most prominent in the posterior temporal region.
Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These results are the same as previous EEGs.  In this individual with longstanding, refractory epilepsy consideration for long-term video EEG monitoring is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and sleep.

report:
HISTORY:

59 y.o. female with a history of childhood

epilepsy, colon cancer, obesity, and DVT presenting with


repetitive seizures and prolonged somnolence in the ED referred

for routine EEG for management of seizure exacerbation and

assessment of mental status change.




MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Dilantin




SEDATION: None listed



TECHNIQUE:


A 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the

International 10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a

NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and


included a single channel of EKG.






EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well

organized symmetric mixture of alpha and beta frequencies, with a


symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR).



There are occasional disorganized bursts of sharply contoured

diffuse theta and delta frequencies.




The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and


amplitude is present.



During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and

fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm, and diffuse


background slowing are seen.




Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with

synchronous and symmetric vertex waves, sleep spindles and

K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.




Mild generalized slowing is present.

There is abundant sharply contoured left temporal polymorphic


slowing.

There is abundant independent sharply contoured right temporal

polymorphic slowing.




EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

1. Very frequent left temporal spikes (F7 > T3 max), activated by


sleep

2. Very frequent left fronto-temporal spikes (F7 > T3 > Fp1/F3

max), activated by sleep

3. Occasional right temporal spikes (F8 > T4 max), activated by


sleep; seen both independently of and synchronously with #2




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None




ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation


are not performed.




EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during

this study.




HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 84 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.




IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:

1. Mild generalized slowing


2. Abundant sharply contoured left temporal polymorphic slowing

3. Abundant independent sharply contoured right temporal


polymorphic slowing

4. Very frequent left temporal spikes (F7 > T3 max), activated by

sleep

5. Very frequent left fronto-temporal spikes (F7 > T3 > Fp1/F3


max), activated by sleep

6. Occasional right temporal spikes (F8 > T4 max), activated by


sleep; seen both independently of and synchronously with #2








CLINICAL CORRELATION:

These findings indicate the presence of multifocal epileptiform


discharges (left temporal and left fronto-temporal > right

temporal), superimposed on bitemporal dysfunction and mild

diffuse cerebral dysfunction.

There were no electrographic seizures captured during this study.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 
1. Mild generalized slowing


2. Abundant sharply contoured left temporal polymorphic slowing

3. Abundant independent sharply contoured right temporal


polymorphic slowing

4. Very frequent left temporal spikes (F7 > T3 max), activated by

sleep

5. Very frequent left fronto-temporal spikes (F7 > T3 > Fp1/F3


max), activated by sleep

6. Occasional right temporal spikes (F8 > T4 max), activated by


sleep; seen both independently of and synchronously with #2

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 19-year-old male with new onset seizure disorder, which was described as generalized tonic-clonic seizure activity.  Prior use of cocaine.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Penicillin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and briefly drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the alpha rhythm is 9.5 Hz, 25 V amplitude, symmetric and reactive. There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in background theta with a single asynchronous burst.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in background theta.  Photic stimulation elicits driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.  Photoelectric artifact was noted.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy. If seizures are an important consideration, a repeat EEG may be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 23-year-old male with a history of seizures in 2003 associated with cocaine use, now admitted with a fall and a seizure prior to the fall.
MEDICATIONS: Morphine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is wearing a hard collar.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9.5 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The patient is drowsy throughout much of the EEG with rhythmic background slowing. Brief stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
There is high amplitude eye movement artifact, some of which is notched.
HR:  50 to 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In this individual with two normal EEGs and at least two seizures, although one associated with cocaine abuse, additional recording in the lab following removal of the hard collar is recommended with generous hyperventilation and photic stimulation to be certain that there is no underlying spike and wave activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 24-year-old with a history of epilepsy, cocaine abuse and severe head trauma after he fell from a train platform. Multiple skull fracture.. craniectomy, pneumocephalus and basilar skull burst. The patient had a seizure on the morning of the 7th.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Midazolam, Labetalol, Ceftazidime
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is intubated and comatose.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Background EEG includes diffuse, slow delta. There is higher amplitude delta in the left frontal region in this markedly slow record. There is a bit faster frontal frequency in the parasagittal regions. Stimulation of the
patient also produced some theta in this region as well.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Slow delta with a slow featureless background.
2. Asymmetry with a bit of a faster frequency on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function. The left hemisphere may be less impacted than the right. No epileptiform features were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Slow delta with a slow featureless background. 2. Asymmetry with a bit of a faster frequency on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 75-year-old, right-handed woman with change in mental status and age-related cerebral atrophy.  She has mild dementia and Brown-SequardÕs syndrome.

MEDICATIONS:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized for age with a 10.5 Hz, 35 ?V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in theta.

HR:  72 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a subject of this age.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  An individual of this age may have a transient metabolic encephalopathy without EEG changes.  In addition, dementing illnesses can occur again without EEG changes.  If appropriate, a follow-up EEG may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG for a subject of this age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 75-year-old, right-handed woman with recurrent seizures or confusion.  Brown-Sequard Syndrome
MEDICATIONS: unknown
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake EEG without hyperventilation or photic simulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is mildly disorganized with a posterior dominant rhythm ranging from 7 to 9 Hz.  There are brief portions of the record where the overall background is better organized.  Throughout the record in wakefulness and drowsiness there is underlying irregular slowing from the left temporal region.
HR:  56 to 80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to:
Mild background disorganization.
Left temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  The features described above are non-specific, but correlation with neuroimaging may be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for a subject of this age due to Mild background disorganization. Left temporal focal slowing.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 36-year-old woman with refractory, generalized epilepsy with tonic-clonic, absence and myoclonic seizures and frequent spike and slow wave activity during her sleep study.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Topiramate.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a symmetric, reactive 8.5 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  In stage II sleep, vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are seen.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing an increase in background theta.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within the limits of normal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Previous EEGs are not available for comparison, but at least in comparison to the polysomnogram, there was no epileptiform activity seen.  Because this is a long-term monitoring baseline, there should be additional studies for this patient with additional EEG monitoring numbers.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within the limits of normal.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 37-year-old  woman with seizures  with VNS implantation  in
2003 now with change in seizure type. MEDICATIONS: Topamax and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital  video EEG is performed in the lab using standard  10-20 system of electrode placement  with one channel  of EKG. Hyperventilation  and  photic  stimulation were performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.



DESCRIPTION OF  THE   RECORD: In  wakefulness,  the  background  EEG  is  symmetric,


continuous, and fairly well organized for age.  There is a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant  alpha rhythm,  which  is  attenuated  with  eyes  opened.    There  is  a  small  amount  of  low  voltage, frontocentral  beta  activity.   As the tracing continues,  alternative  sharp  waves  in  the posterior region, as well as 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity were seen in drowsiness.  The 3 Hz activities repeatedly occurred  in drowsiness, lasting from 1 to 3.5 seconds without change in behavior. This activity seemed to emanate from the left central and temporal regions.   No clinical behavior was observed  on  the  video  can1era. Drowsiness  is  characterized  by  a  mixed frequency  of  brain activity,  but deeper stages of sleep  were not achieved.   Hyperventilation  mildly  increased  the slow theta activity on the background.  Post-hyperventilation, the patient became drowsy.  Photic stimulation elicits driving.

ID:  60BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  alternative sharp activity in the posterior region.
2.   3 Hz spike and slow wave activity seen in drowsiness, repeatedly originating  from the left central and temporal areas- C3 and T3 areas.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: This abnormal EEG reflects an underlying pathologic process of the brain and provides a partial mechanism for epilepsy in this patient.  The occurrence of 3 Hz spike and slow wave activity is a likely epileptogenic in origin and  bears clinical  significance. However,  the electric  artifact from  the VNS device should be excluded.    A repeat EEG  with careful attention to the VNS device is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.  alternative sharp activity in the posterior region. 2.   3 Hz spike and slow wave activity seen in drowsiness, repeatedly originating  from the left central and temporal areas- C3 and T3 areas.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 39-year-old woman with a long history of refractory epilepsy and seizures in June and July of 2006, both of which seem to have been provoked.  No seizures since July.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Phenytoin, VNS.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  Early drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm to 8 Hz.   Hyperventilation is performed with good effort, producing an increase in theta.  Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
There is a single abnormality identified in this record in the transition just as the patient is drifting off to sleep and it does seem to elicit an arousal.  This is a frontally predominant spike and slow wave complex with a poly spike and slow wave component reaching amplitudes up to 200 uV.  It is symmetric and frontally predominant.  The whole entire entity includes a burst of approximately one second without clear correlate, but with an alerting.
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.	An isolated, frontally predominant spike and slow wave complex.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to previous studies, this EEG demonstrated a relative paucity of epileptiform activity.  This may be due to the little sleep that was recorded in this record.  Of note, this patient has a history of prominent spike and slow wave activity in sleep.  The observation of an arousal in association with epileptiform activity may be part of this patient’s underlying sleep disturbance.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.An isolated, frontally predominant spike and slow wave complex.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 45-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 12, nocturnal tonic-clonic and daytime absence seizures, vagal nerve stimulator implanted.  The patient reported an increase in tonic-clonic seizures around the time of her period associated with stress and then an increase in staring spells.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin and Zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was extremely drowsy throughout the EEG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 7.5 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontal central beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in rhythmic theta.  There are rare, left anterior temporal sharp waves noted, and a small amount of left anterior temporal slowing.
Photic stimulation was technically somewhat complicated by muscle artifact, but a driving response was elicited.
Heart rate 72 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a technically somewhat challenging but abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing in apparent wakefulness.
Rare left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG differs from previous studies in that there is a bit more background slowing and that there are focal rather than generalized epileptiform features.  These findings may be correlated with this patient's clinical picture.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a technically somewhat challenging but abnormal EEG due to Background slowing in apparent wakefulness. Rare left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 60-year-old, right-handed woman with seizures, hepatitis C, hypertension, and stroke admitted with severe headache and tightness in her chest.
MEDICATIONS: Plavix, Neurontin, many others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz, 70 V posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Prominent temporal wicket is identified in drowsiness as well as an increase in frontocentral beta.  Other features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.
HR:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  Normal EEG does not exclude the diagnosis of epilepsy and if seizures are an important consideration, a repeat tracing could be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG in wakefulness and drowsiness.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 62-year-old woman with epilepsy, awoke 10/24/04 tired, confused, dizzy, and incontinent with left-sided weakness and numbness.  DM, HTN, CHF, CVA, epilepsy, and sleep apnea.
MEDICATIONS: Neurontin, Zoloft, and Celebrex.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slow in organization for a subject of this age.  There is an 8 Hz posterior dominant rhythm.  There is snore artifact, but there is also arrhythmic delta activity picked up from either temporal region, independently, and occasionally bilaterally.  That from the right seems to have an underlying C4 sharp wave. As the patient becomes drowsy, the arrhythmic delta from the right temporal region is more prominent.  In addition, the sharp waves associated with it are also a bit more prominent.  In later portions of the record, as the patient reaches sleep, the background is more synchronous, lower amplitude.  The sharp waves on one or two occasions spread to the right posterior temporal and parietal regions, and there are rare left temporal sharp waves.
HR:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized background slowing.
Arrhythmic delta activity identified independently or bilaterally in the temporal regions.
Primarily right mid-temporal sharp waves, occasionally posterior temporal sharp waves, and three rare left temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This tracing supports a partial or localization-related mechanism for seizures.  No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Mild generalized background slowing. Arrhythmic delta activity identified independently or bilaterally in the temporal regions. Primarily right mid-temporal sharp waves, occasionally posterior temporal sharp waves, and three rare left temporal sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old, right-handed woman with diabetes, stroke, hypertension, and seizures for two years.  Migraine headaches with frontal headache, photophobia.  Recurrent complex partial seizures associated with discontinuation of antiepileptic medications.  Seizures are characterized by a clammy, sweaty feeling and loss of consciousness with incontinence.  No previous EEGs were available for comparison.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Albuterol.  The patient was otherwise not able to list her medications.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 30 to 50 V posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  The patient rapidly drifts into deeper stages of sleep with relatively symmetric, theta frequency activity as well as vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.  In later stage II sleep, the background remains rich in beta frequency activity.  There are occasional bursts of shifting theta or delta.  Later stage II sleep is symmetric with abundant K complexes, spindles, and vertex waves.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing symmetric slowing.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is asleep and no significant driving response is identified.
HR:  90 BPM, rare APCs.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No significant focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  To further characterize this patient’s seizures, a repeat tracing with a more prolonged recording could be of use.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for a subject of this age.

report:
HISTORY:
A 62-year-old-woman with change in mental status, aphasic Evaluate for delirium, stroke.
MEDICATIONS:
1. Diovan
2. Glyburide
3. Insulin
4. Methimazole
INTRODUCTION:
Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:
In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG is slow and disorganized with primarily a theta frequency background and
a posterior dominant rhythm which is approximately7 Hz on the left, slower on the right. There is shifting arrhythmic delta
activity. There are also some bursts of sharply contoured slowing and sharp waves in the left mid temporal region.
Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
Heart rate 84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:
Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Shifting slowing a nd diffuse sharply contoured slowing on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
The sharply contoured slowing may be correlated with the history. The generalized background slowing and arrhythmic
slowing are compatible with a bihemispheric disturbance. Renal failure, and/or cerebrovascular disease can also
contribute to this picture. Previous EEGs were not available for review.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION Abnormal EEG due to 1. Generalized background slowing. 2. Shifting slowing a nd diffuse sharply contoured slowing on the left.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old, right-handed male with a single episode of loss of consciousness with foaming of the mouth and postictal confusion.  Treated with Seroquel and Zoloft for insomnia and depression.  History of a single seizure in the swimming pool as a toddler.
MEDICATIONS: Zoloft, Seroquel.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 60 V posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Posterior slow waves of youth are identified.  Drowsiness is characterized by hypersynchronous, rhythmic theta followed by vertex waves.  The patient seems to be somewhat drowsy and he drifts off to sleep or demonstrates hypersynchronous theta early in drowsiness.
Hyperventilation is performed with good effort producing vigorous bursts of high amplitude, frontally predominant delta activity but no definite spike and slow wave activity.
Photic stimulation elicits well-formed driving at intermediate and faster flash frequencies.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definite focal or epileptiform features were identified in this record.  There is prominent, hypersynchronous slowing in hyperventilation.  Comparison with childhood EEGs could be useful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits for age.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old male with a childhood seizure with a complex partial seizure versus syncope this past winter.
MEDICATIONS: Previously on Zoloft.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake through stage II sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 10 Hz, 50 to 70 V posterior dominant rhythm, which is higher amplitude on the right compared to the left.  There is also a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.
The major abnormality is some subtle, isolated focal slowing from the left temporal region with a mixture of primarily theta but a smaller amount of delta activity.  Other features in stage I and into stage II sleep are prominent POSTS, which are higher amplitude on the left, and at times there is an appearance of almost a very subtle posterior temporal focus of isolated 3 Hz activity.  In addition, there is a discrete sharp wave identified again in the left mid to anterior region, which is identified in drowsiness and into stage II sleep.  This is also elicited in apparent wakefulness around the time of photic in relaxed wakefulness.  It occurs over a background of relatively sharply contoured activity with the potential for a normal variant such as wicket, but there seems to be only this discharge from the left temporal region.  There is no other phase reversal on the contralateral side and there is a bit of focal slowing underlying this rhythmic, sharply contoured activity.  All discharges are relatively small and discrete, but again identified on one occasion in relaxed wakefulness and on rare occasions into stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation produces vigorous background delta.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric driving. 	HR:  60 BPM
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Subtle, left temporal focal slowing seen primarily in the anterior temporal region but on some occasions in the posterior temporal region with a small discrete sharp wave.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This activity is outside of the range of possibilities for a normal variant and consideration for a partial mechanism for epilepsy is recommended.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Subtle, left temporal focal slowing seen primarily in the anterior temporal region but on some occasions in the posterior temporal region with a small discrete sharp wave.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 78-year-old, right-handed woman with confusion, progressive dementia, and hypertension.
MEDICATIONS: Procardia, Aricept.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 31-year-old male with childhood onset refractory complex partial epilepsy with butterflies in the stomach and occasional secondary generalization.
MEDICATIONS: Carbamazepine, Lamotrigine, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a 9.25 Hz, 70 to 80 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, which dramatically increases the amplitude of the background and produces a small amount of bitemporal slowing.  Occasionally the bitemporal slowing shows shifting asymmetries and may be irregular.  On one occasion, it is sharply contoured and irregular on the left following A.B.   Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha, slow rolling eye movements, and somewhat irregular, sharply contoured theta identified from the temporal regions, left greater than right.  Vertex waves are seen in stage I sleep.  During photic stimulation, the patient is drowsy and during this portion of the record, there are left temporal sharp and slow wave complexes with bursts of sharply contoured activity during photic.  No driving response is elicited and after photic, the patient drifts off to stage II sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles.
HR:  70 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Left temporal spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes with associated focal slowing elicited in proximity to but not by photic stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In contrast to previous EEGs, this is the first EEG that demonstrates epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Left temporal spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes with associated focal slowing elicited in proximity to but not by photic stimulation.

report:
HISTORY:

72 y.o. female with a history of previous seizures, referred for routine EEG for
evaluation of paroxysmal events.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

topiramate (TOPAMAX) 200 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 2 times daily.meclizine,
(ANTIVERT), ciprofloxacin HCl (CIPRO), desloratadine (CLARINEX), loratadine
(CLARITIN),diphenhydrAMINE (ANTI-ITCH, DIPHENHYDRAMINE,) 2 % cream, baclofen (LIORESAL),
fluticasone (FLONASE) 50 mcg/actuation nasal spray, ketoconazole (NIZORAL) 2 % cream,
naproxen (NAPROSYN), aspirin EC 325 mg EC tablet, mometasone (NASONEX) 50 mcg/actuation
nasal spray, Cholecalciferol, Vitamin D3, (VITAMIN D-3), lovastatin (MEVACOR) 40 mg tablet,
alendronate (FOSAMAX) 70 mg tablet,




SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:







A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of poorly organized low to medium
amplitude and reactive 8-8.5 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR). A large amount of low to
medium amplitude frontally predominant 18-25 Hz activity is seen. Moderate amounts of eye blink,
muscle, and EKG artifact are seen.




During drowsiness, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm and diffuse
background slowing are seen.



Very brief stage II sleep is characterized by attenuation of muscle artifact and beta activity along with
increased amounts of bilaterally symmetric medium amplitude delta and theta slowing.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


None


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 58 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:









This is an mildly abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to mild background disorganization
and slowing of dominant posterior rhythmic activity during wakefulness. These are nonspecific
abnormalities and indicate a mild disturbance of cerebral activity such as that seen with a variety of
mild generalized encephalopathies of various etiologies. No persistent focal slowing, no clinical or
electrographic seizure activity, and no pathologic paroxysmal epileptiform discharges were recorded.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old male with metastatic lung cancer.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and insulin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The awake background EEG is well organized with an 11 Hz, 50 uV posterior dominant rhythm.  The most striking abnormality in this record is a high amplitude spike and slow wave, poly spike and slow wave complex identified from the right hemisphere with a generous field of spread including C4, P4, and T4.  The focal spiking may be intermittent, periodic, or occur in transient clusters.  When the spiking stops, the posterior dominant rhythm on the right is well defined and there are portions of the record where it is defined bilaterally.  As the patient becomes drowsy, the epileptiform activity becomes increasingly periodic and the EEG develops a small degree of discontinuity in sleep around the epileptiform activity.
Photic stimulation elicits primarily a photoelectric effect, but there is a suggestion of a driving response underneath that.
HR:  118 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with a relatively generous field of spread including the parietal, central, and posterior temporal regions.
Associated focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No seizures were recorded.  This EEG supports a structural abnormality as well as a partial localization method for seizures.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Focal epileptiform activity from the right hemisphere with a relatively generous field of spread including the parietal, central, and posterior temporal regions. Associated focal slowing.

report:
History:	29 year old male with a history of seizures. Last seizure in 2013.  This is a follow up
Medications:	Tegretol, Keppra
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  The AP gradient is weak.  Excess diffuse admixed 50-75 uV, 5-
7Hz activity is present throughout the recording.  During brief drowsiness, the alpha rhythm
attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely.
No focal slowing is present.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse
symmetric background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Diffuse slowing, polymorphic, mild
Disorganization, mild
No stage 2 sleep
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 23-minute EEG due to mild background slowing and
disorganization. These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of mild diffuse cerebral
dysfunction.  No epileptiform discharges are present, but stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If
clinically indicated, repeat EEG with sleep recording may provide additional information.
IMPRESSION:

No reactivity

etiologically nonspecific.

etiologically nonspecific

report:

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Markedly abnormal background with marked asymmetry.
A slow pattern on the left.
A pattern that is also abnormal on the right with C4 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a process involving the left hemisphere more significantly than the right.  This may reflect the  bilateral nature of this patient's multiple CNS insults.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Markedly abnormal background with marked asymmetry. A slow pattern on the left. A pattern that is also abnormal on the right with C4 sharp waves.

report:

2. 	Occasional sharp waves from the left with associated slowing.

Description:

No epileptiform discharges
No stage 2 sleep
Focal slowing, polymorphic, occasional, mild
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL 22-minute awake and drowsy EEG due to occasional mild left anterior
temporal slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically non-
specific, but possibly structural in origin.

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes. SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric and reactive, with a fairly organized mixture of alpha, beta, and
theta frequencies, with fragments of a symmetric and reactive posterior dominant rhythm that
approaches 8 Hertz. The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present
but suboptimal.




Drowsiness and sleep are not captured.



Mild generalized slowing is present.

There is occasional left frontal polymorphic slowing.



There are frequent spikey waveforms over F7, F8 that appear most consistent with lateral rectus spikes.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.




EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 120 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake only  routine EEG due to:

1. Mild generalized slowing and suboptimal organization


2. Occasional left frontal polymorphic slowing

3. Tachycardia


CLINICAL CORRELATION:



These findings are etiologically nonspecific indicators of the presence of left frontal dysfunction
superimposed on a mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction.


Tachycardia is noted on a single EKG lead.



A call was placed to this patient's long term care facility to notify them of the tachycardia.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake only  routine EEG due to 
1. Mild generalized slowing and suboptimal organization


2. Occasional left frontal polymorphic slowing

3. Tachycardia

report:

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 58-year-old woman with a remote history of alcohol withdrawal seizure admitted with acute renal failure.  Patient previously evaluated for right-sided symptoms with slurred speech, asterixis or myoclonus the previous day.  Multiple medical problems.
MEDICATIONS: Lovastatin, Clindamycin, Ativan, and others.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is still intubated at the time of the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is lethargic throughout much of the record.  The primary frequency of the background is 5 to 7 Hz theta frequency activity. There are occasional bursts of shifting arrhythmic delta activity, as well as bursts of generalized delta or frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity.  There is EKG artifact picked up in the temporal electrodes.
Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta and a decrease in delta.
HR:  80 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Poor organization.
FIRDA.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Compared to a recent, previous study, this EEG demonstrates significant background slowing.  These features may be due to the patient’s acute medical illness, renal failure, or the CNS acting medications she received the previous day.  No epileptiform activity was identified in either record.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing. Poor organization. FIRDA.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 54-year-old male who presented with the complaint of conjunctivitis and then went on to have status epilepticus requiring large doses of Ativan. INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient is sedated, but becomes extremely agitated with any kind of tactile stimuli.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG shows diffuse beta activity, medium-to-low voltage.  With any sort of stimulation, there is an increase in frontal delta.  There is spontaneous variability in the record.  The overall pattern is relatively low voltage.  There are occasional bursts of shifting delta.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with primarily a beta pattern.
Bursts of delta with tactile stimulation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This study contrast to a March 2004 EEG for this individual, which was normal.  No epileptiform features have been identified in either record.  Given the profound agitation and the high doses of benzodiazepines used, consideration for alcohol or benzodiazepine withdrawal is appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Replacement of normal background with primarily a beta pattern. Bursts of delta with tactile stimulation.

report:

report:

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.

Following hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, there is an increase in background rhythmic theta.  Features of sleep include vertex waves and occasional spindles. report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 20-year-old, right-handed male with epilepsy since age 12.  Last seizure one week ago with postictal drowsiness.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with a high amplitude 50 to 75 uV posterior dominant rhythm of 10.5 Hz. Hyperventilation does not activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits symmetric bilateral driving. Following photic stimulation, just at the close of the EEG, there is a single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.
HR:  ___ BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
A single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: A single burst of epileptiform activity does not make this record abnormal, however, the activity described above is compatible with a primary generalized epilepsy.  It may be more cost effective to compare this EEG with previous, childhood studies rather than repeating a study.  Alternatively, if additional mechanisms are needed to characterize epileptiform activity, a fasting, sleep deprived study with generous hyperventilation could be effective.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to A single burst of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity of 6 Hz in duration.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  64 year old right handed man with heart murmur, seizures since 2002, prostate cancer with seizures described as loss of consciousness with generalized tonic-clonic shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Metoprolol, Ropinirole, Colchicine.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8.5 Hz and which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures which included hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves at 5-7 Hz seen during wakefulness throughout the recording.
SLEEP:  The patient did achieve stage 1 and stage 2, but the sleep latency was fairly short and he would quickly go into stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that there was a short sleep latency and consideration for a sleep disorder should be placed.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Mild generalized slowing.

report:

MEDICATIONS: Carbatrol, Zocor, HCTZ.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The video has been deleted from the data provided.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing an increase in rhythmic slowing.  Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is becoming drowsy. IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 60-year-old woman with absence epilepsy and tonic­ clonic  seizures.  No  tonic-clonic   seizures  for  the  last   three   years,  but  currently experiencing petit absence attacks.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background is well organized with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record and exquisitely accentuates brief bursts of 4 to 5.5 Hz spike and wave activity. The activity is not sustained, however, in HV the patient reports feeling "a little twitchy" even with a handful of discharges. The longest duration of discharges is four seconds and is at the end of HV, as the patient is becoming drowsy and testing is not performed. There is also a pair of sharp and slow wave complexes identified in the left with similar morphology, but with  a bit of localization.    Drowsiness also seems to accentuate the generalized epileptiform  activity.   Photic stimulation does not produce spike and wave activity.
HR:  72BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Previous EEGs were not available at tills time for comparison.  A sample of the epileptiform activity was printed out and should have been provided with this report.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1.  Generalized spike and wave activity.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old left handed man with history of seizures, presents with possible status epilepticus with past medical history of stroke, hepatitis C cirrhosis, traumatic brain injury, now with EEG for myoclonus versus seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Albuterol, Ipratropium, Dopamine, Ceftriaxone, Pantoprazole, Versed, Fentanyl.
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures, now with myoclonic jerks.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with addition of an anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.   The patient was recorded in wakefulness.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or normal frontal central beta.  The patient did not appear to go into normal sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with low-amplitude 20-30 mV seen continuously.
Throughout the recording, there is low-amplitude sharply contoured periodic discharges seen maximally at CZ occurring about 1 Hz with no clear clinical correlate, most consistent with CZ sharp waves and periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges.
SEIZURES:  None.
Of note, during the recording, the technician did stimulate the patient, and the patient appeared to be eye fluttering and moving rhythmically, but there is no EEG correlate to this eye movement seen or fluttering of the eyes.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves.
Central PLEDs.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction and irritability in the central region which may be due to an underlying lesion or focus of irritation.  In addition, there is evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to utility.  No seizures were clearly seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Generalized slow waves. Central PLEDs.

a 29 y.o. female with a history of IVDA, TBI and epilepsy in the past, found down
with ICH referred for routine EEG for screening for subclinical seizures.

methylPREDNISolone sodium succinate (Solu-MEDROL) 250 mg in sodium chloride 0.9 % 100 mL
IVPB
enoxaparin (LOVENOX) injection 40 mg

valproate (DEPACON) 500 mg in sodium chloride 0.9 % 100 mL IVPB

niMODipine (NIMOTOP) capsule 30 mg


sodium chloride 0.9 % injection (flush) 10 mL

sodium chloride 0.9 % injection (flush) 10 mL

ondansetron (PF) (ZOFRAN) injection 4 mg


diphenhydrAMINE (BENADRYL) capsule 25 mg

levETIRAacetam (KEPPRA) solution 500 mg


oxyCODONE-acetaminophen (PERCOCET) 5-325 mg per tablet 2 tablet- patient required pre-
treatment with Percocet for the EEG

Had LTG as well.


TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically  satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG.  Patient was reluctant to cooperate with the test.


MRI demonstrated:  Acute to subacute hemorrhage in the right parasagittal frontal lobe


and right basal ganglia with associated mass effect as above.. Encephalomalacia/gliosis in the left
anterior temporal and left frontal lobes with chronic blood products likely related to remote trauma.
Small focus of chronic hemorrhage in the left basal ganglia.




EEG BACKGROUND:


The waking background is actively abnormal and asymmetric.  It is characterized in asymmetry.  The
left hemisphere is slightly disorganized but with the posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz 30 uV.  There
is excess theta, intermittent arrhythmic delta activity and greater variability than anticipated in
wakefulness on the left.  The right hemisphere is characterized by significant disruption of the
posterior dominant rhythm, disruption of faster frequency activity and bursts of relatively rhythmic 1-3
Hz delta activity maximum in the frontal regions, sometimes occurring in bursts lasting 3-5 seconds



Generalized slowing is present.


Focal slowing is present.

Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in rhythmic frontal delta bilaterally

EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:


No definite spikes


OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


FIRDA.


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: none


EVENTS: There are  no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 121 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:




This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:

1. Marked slowing on the right with bursts of frontal delta


2. Bilateral slowing and disorganization.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:


The bursts of prominent, paroxysmal frontal delta are in the region of this patient's hemorrhage.
Because of the prominent paroxysmal quality, additional monitoring may be of value.

This EEG supports a structural abnormality in the right hemisphere, superimposed upon a
bihemispheric process, congruent with the findings outlined by imaging.  No seizures were recorded.
The issue of long-term monitoring was discussed with the ICU team.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 



This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to 
1. Marked slowing on the right with bursts of frontal delta


2. Bilateral slowing and disorganization.

report:
History:	34 year old female with history of seizures since childhood.  She reportedly had at
least 2 seizures in the last week.
Medications:	Hydrochlorothiazide, Tegretol, zoloft, Ambien
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Routine, awake & drowsy
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well formed and modulated 9 Hz alpha activity that
attenuates with eye opening.  PDR is better formed and modulated over the left.  There is an
anterior-to-posterior frequency-amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes
anteriorly.  During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely,
followed by symmetric vertex waves.
There is continuous interhemispheric voltage asymmetry with lower voltages over the right.
Additionally, there is paucity of faster frequencies over the right hemisphere, especially over the
anterior and median quadrants.  Semi-rhythmic sharply contoured delta activity at 1-1.25 Hz is
observed over the right frontotemporal region during and following hyperventilation.  Occasional
right frontotemporal sharp waves are noted.  Maximal scalp negativity occurs over F8, T2, Fp2 and
F4 electrodes.  These discharges become more apparent during photic stimulation.  No clear
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces no effect.
Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) produces semi-rhythmic sharply
contoured right frontotemporal delta activity and accentuates right frontotemporal sharp waves.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, right hemispheric, mild-to-moderate, especially over
Attenuation, continuous, mild, right hemispheric
Sharp waves, occasional, right frontotemporal, accentuated by photic stimulation
Other, right frontotemporal, focal semi-rhythmic delta is seen with photic stimulation
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and drowsy 24-minute EEG due to mild-to-moderate right
hemispheric slowing that is most pronounced over the anterior and middle quadrants and occasional
right frontotemporal epileptiform discharges. Focal slowing and voltage attenuation over the right
is suggestive of focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology.  A potential epileptogenic
focus emanates from the right frontotemporal region.  Given accentuation of epileptiform
discharges and focal slowing with photic stimulation, this EEG is suggestive of photosensitive
seizures.  Please correlate clinically electrographic seizures are captured.

focus emanates from the right frontotemporal region.  Given accentuation of epileptiform

seizures.  Please correlate clinically electrographic seizures are captured

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  There is generous,  low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized by slow rolling eye movements and an increase in beta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.  Photic stimulation elicits driving at intermediate flash frequencies.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male with status epilepticus earlier this morning status post 10 mg of Ativan, Dilantin, and Keppra. History of cervical myelopathy. Intubated and paralyzed prior to the EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra, Ativan, Etomidate, Fentanyl, Versed, ROCURONIUM
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is starting to emerge from paralysis and demonstrates stiffening and movements.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is a bit quieter. Activity demonstrates a slow pattern with some rhythmic mixed theta and delta on the left with a lower voltage, slower, a bit more suppressed pattern on the right, particularly in the temporal regions.
Stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting with an increase in muscle as well as alpha and theta frequency activity. During the EEG, the patient starts to wake up, move around, and cough. After this, there is a more alert pattern with more theta frequency and alpha frequency activity from the left, but the right remains quite slow. By the end of the record in this very sharply contoured record, there was a suggestion of underlying sharp activity versus part of the fast activity at F3. In addition, more sharply contoured slowing is seen at T4-T6.
HR: 84 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere.
2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe, bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function as would be expected following the use of sedative, hypnotic medications. The focal slowing and rare sharp waves on the right are compatible with past right temporal hemorrhage. Additional evaluation of this patient's cerebral function may be needed. Ongoing EEG monitoring was undertaken to make sure no additional seizures occurred.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Nearly continuous focal slowing on the right hemisphere. 2. Occasional T4-T6 sharps and question F3 sharps as well.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 57 year old right handed male admitted with 4 seizures, alcohol abuse, past history of intracerebral hemorrhage, hepatitis C, stroke, and hypertension.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Tylenol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm identified on the left. Faster frequency activity is attenuated on the right. The patient is conversant with the tech. This patient has an event during the EEG. The event occurs at 10:08 a.m. It is characterized by staring, jerking of the head from side to side. The EEG is remarkable for some sharp waves and some motion artifacts. The sharp waves are seen in the right frontocentral region. There is significant muscle activity. The patient is conversant during the spell. No postictal slowing is noted. Photic stimulation elicits a brief driving response on the left.

HR: 78 bpm

IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Focal slowing from the right.
2. An event during the EEG without impairment of awareness. Although there is some artifact, there are some discharges in the same region as the patient's sharp waves. While the event might not be considered a simple partial or a complex partial seizure, the motor activity observed may be linked to the epileptiform activity elicited from the right frontocentral region which could have produced the features described above.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION/CLINICAL CORRELATION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Focal slowing from the right

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 55-year-old, right-handed woman with COPD and epilepsy starting two years ago. Last seizure three weeks ago characterized by numbness and shaking lasting for five to ten minutes.  No previous EEGs were available.
MEDICATIONS: Patient does not recall.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. This is an awake through stage II sleep record with photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is markedly sharply contoured with a 9 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm with prominent temporal wicket seen from either region.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a prominent increase in theta frequency activity.  Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep.  Photic stimulation is attempted, but the patient has drifted back into stage II sleep.   Occasional snore arousals are noted in the background.
HR:  78 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is a very sharply contoured background and a great deal of temporal wicket, but no definite epileptiform activity.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study may be of value.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits in wakefulness through stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old female with epilepsy and dizziness.  No other information is available.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Dilantin, and Buspirone.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. The patient has an event during the EEG. Hyperventilation is performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Although the patient is markedly drowsy throughout much of the record, there is a 9 Hz, 30 uV posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and theta.  Hyperventilation is performed with fair effort, producing an increase in the amplitude of the background.  At the end of hyperventilation, the patient has a single episode of both shoulders jerking at 11:37:07.  Slowly, at 11:53, she starts to have rocking of the head from side to side and then has rocking from side to side with alternating movements of the hands, with hands coming up and going down and then head rocking from side to side.  During this event, although there is some movement artifact, the EEG otherwise demonstrates an awake pattern.  The technologist interacts with the patient during the event giving her a code word.  The patient has multiple different behaviors during this episode including brief hyperextension of the back and then slow rocking from side to side.
Towards the end of the behavior, the tech uses a nasal tickle.  The patient looks apprehensive and at one point turns away just briefly, but doesn’t move substantially.  She does blink to threat during the event, and towards the end of the event, seems upset or angry and is staring away from the direction of the technologist.  As the technologist moves around the room, however, the patient can be seen to track the tech with her eyes.  After the event is over, the patient tells the tech that the only thing she can remember is that her name is [patient’s name].
HR:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Although the patient was initially quite drowsy, there is no epileptiform activity.  This patient had a complex and prolonged behavioral event without EEG change.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 52-year-old woman with epilepsy and non-epileptic seizures starting several years ago.  The technologist reported that the patient has tonic­ clonic seizures, tongue biting, incontinence, but had a behavioral spell without EEG change on most recent EEG.
MEDICATIONS: Trileptal, Neurontin, Paxil, and Singulair.
INTRODUCTION: This is a one-hour digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard  10-20 system  of  electrode  placement  with  one  channel  of  EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE  RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a
10 Hz, 40 uV posterior dominant rhythm and a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing.
Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.   The patient seems to make the transition to stage I sleep,  but  then  spontaneously arouses.   Hyperventilation  produces a modest amount of background slowing.  Stage II sleep is characterized by abundant POSTS and spindles. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response.
HR: 72BPM. IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal or epileptiform features were identified in this
record.  In comparison to a previous record, both studies show normal cerebral activity, but no behavioral events were recorded today.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

report:

INTRODUCTION: 	Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This patient's previous EEGs were not available for comparison today. This is a 1-hour EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 4-year-old male with a one-year history of epilepsy; last seizure three weeks ago with foaming at the mouth. History of staring spells, generalized shaking lasting two to three minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was performed.   This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well enough organized for age with a posterior dominant rhythm averaging 6 Hz, sometimes somewhat faster, reaching amplitudes up to 100 uV.  Features of drowsiness include hypersynchronous rhythmic slowing.  Vertex waves are identified with brief sleep epochs and then spontaneous arousals. Hyperventilation produces rhythmic slowing.
Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Although there are multiple episodes of hypersynchronous rhythmic 5 Hz activity, the static can be re-reviewed and is without epileptiform activity and is simply characteristic of a prominent hypnagogic hypersynchrony.
HR:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Additional EEG recording including capturing more extended sleep may be important to characterize this child’s epilepsy if previous EEGs have not done so.  Photic stimulation may also be employed.  In comparison to previous EEGs, this study was of better quality technically, but neither studies identified epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 5-year-old male with epilepsy admitted on the 16th after he fell down the stairs and had a convulsion and a laceration on his cheek lasting five minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin and Tylenol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  This is this child’s third EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximal wakefulness, there is a 6.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive.  There are portions of the record when the child is awake when the background is appropriately organized for age.
The major abnormalities in this record include complex epileptiform activity, which can be best viewed at fast paper speed of six seconds per page and/or average reference.  These include spike and slow wave complexes, which are high in amplitude and sometimes seem almost electropositive in the mid-temporal region, but in most of the montages are maximum at C3.  They are variable with some having a much more generous field of spread to the frontocentral region or left hemisphere and others more restricted.  They are picked up by volume conduction in the contralateral hemisphere.  In addition, there are some generalized frontally predominant spike and slow wave discharges, some of which are 3.5 to 4 Hz, but which are slightly irregular.  As the child drifts off to sleep, marked background slowing is observed and prominent, high amplitude slow spike and wave complexes are identified.  These are picked up in the frontocentral region, but more so on the left.
As the child drifts off to sleep, he is lying on his side, away from the camera and towards his mother.  Initially, he seems to have jerking forward of the head.  Subsequently, he seems almost to be having a salaam-like seizure as he drifts off to sleep, jerking towards his mother with his arms coming up a little bit.  This seems to elicit an arousal from sleep.  The epileptiform activity is high in amplitude, but some sections of the sleep record seem to demonstrate a sleep pattern that is remarkable for prominent attenuation of the typical morphologies in sleep with this high amplitude spike and slow wave pathology, most prominent in the frontal regions and again with an unusual field but with more of a predominance to the left hemisphere.  The child does fall off to sleep at 12:51.
HR:  114 BPM.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Prominent epileptiform activity with complex epileptiform activity, slow spike and wave activity, and focal spike and slow wave activity, but activity that on the whole raises concerns about a process involving the left hemisphere.
Concerns that the background activity in sleep is slower than expected particularly in the frontocentral regions, left greater than right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings must be correlated with imaging and clinical exam at this juncture.  They differ from the two previous EEGs, which were not successful in identifying epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Prominent epileptiform activity with complex epileptiform activity, slow spike and wave activity, and focal spike and slow wave activity, but activity that on the whole raises concerns about a process involving the left hemisphere. Concerns that the background activity in sleep is slower than expected particularly in the frontocentral regions, left greater than right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: This is a 57-year-old, right-handed woman with cerebellar degeneration, myoclonus, and hepatic cirrhosis with tremor, confusion, and encephalopathy.

Underlying this, there is some intermittent arrhythmic delta activity sometimes sharply contoured in the left temporal region.  Vertex waves and spindles are seen in stage II sleep, but there remains a fair amount of muscle in sleep.  Hyperventilation is performed with poor effort, but does seem to produce both generalized rhythmic frontal slowing, as well as accentuating some of the focal slowing from the left. HR:  66 BPM.

Generalized background slowing and poor organization.
Superimposed focal slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were identified in this record, however, given the amount of muscle artifact noted in the background, if epileptiform activity is of importance, a repeat sleep record may be necessary.  No periodic changes were seen.  In this individual who was evaluated for Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, not all individuals demonstrate the characteristic pseudoperiodic findings initially and additional studies over a 12 week period may be necessary.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to Generalized background slowing and poor organization. Superimposed focal slowing from the left.

report:

report:
History:	58 year old woman with a reported history of seizures since -1985. Medications:	Topamax
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic
Description:
Background voltages are low.  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low voltage beta activity that attenuates with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV,  18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  The majority of the background consists of low amplitude diffuse beta activity.   During drowsiness, the alpha rhythm attenuates, and 5-7Hz slow waves appear diffusely, followed by symmetric vertex waves.   During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.   Frequent positive sharp waves occur bilaterally and independently in the occipital regions during drowsiness  and light sleep.
Occasional low voltage sharp waves are seen over the left fronto-temporal region (Fp1/F7/F3). A benign variant (BETS, benign epileptiform transients of sleep) cannot entirely be excluded.
Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with good cooperation, and produces mild diffuse symmetric background slowing. Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates. A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate 54 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Sharp waves, occasional, left frontotemporal
Interpretation:
This is an abnormal 1-hour awake and asleep EEG due to: 1. Left frontotemporal sharp waves (Fp1/F7/F3). While these sharp waves are most likely epileptiform, a benign variant (BETS) cannot entirely be excluded. Of note, low voltage backgrounds are a benign variant in the adult population.
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an abnormal 1-hour awake and asleep EEG due to: 1. Left frontotemporal sharp waves (Fp1/F7/F3). While these sharp waves are most likely epileptiform, a benign variant (BETS) cannot entirely be excluded. Of note, low voltage backgrounds are a benign variant in the adult population
