report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 59 year old right handed woman with severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, ARDS, likely metastatic and aggressive breast malignancy with multiple embolic infarcts including cerebellum and bilateral thalamic and ACA. History of epilepsy.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Thiamine, Zocor, Lovenox, Protonix, Lisinopril, Linezolid, Cefepime
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is intubated, unresponsive and examined during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates essentially continuous pattern rich in theta frequency activity. Arrhythmic delta activity is prominent in the posterior regions, right more so than the left. Some of this is sharply contoured. In addition, on 1 or 2 occasions, there seems to be a left frontotemporal sharp wave. There is intermittent attenuation and/or disruption of the theta with slower arrhythmic delta activity. Stimulation of the patient does seem to produce an increase in theta.
HR: 116 bpm
IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the posterior region.
3. Some sharply contoured transience in the record including posterior temporal and left frontal.
4. Intermittent background attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a significant, bihemispheric pathology particularly in the posterior regions. The presence of reactivity is a positive prognostic finding, but the intermittent attenuation is a worrisome prognostic finding in this individual with multiple medical problems and bilateral cerebral ischemia.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Markedly abnormal EEG due to 1. Background slowing. 2. Arrhythmic delta activity most prominent in the posterior region. 3. Some sharply contoured transience in the record including posterior temporal and left frontal. 4. Intermittent background attenuation.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	24-year-old female, past medical history of Wegener's granulomatosis, kidney transplant in 1999, end stage renal disease on peritoneal dialysis,  hypertension, anemia, and deep venous thrombosis, that presents with new onset seizure, generalized tonic, clonic, with loss of consciousness  and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Calcitriol, Aranesp, Senipar, Simvastatin, Mupirocin, Heparin, Moxifloxacin, Percocet, Phenergan.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. The patient had a coughing spell while in the lab.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness the background EEG is well­ organized with 9.5, Hz 50, 50-70 microvolts posterior dominant rhythm. A normal variant is observed in the background with rhythmic mid temporal, 5 Hz activity in the temporal regions, right or left. The technologist tested the patient on multiple occasions with stimulation of the patient always terminates these strains at 5 Hz flat top shaped activity, which may be unilateral or bilaterally.
At 11: 30: 54: The patient is sitting comfortably and has a heart rate of 84. She has a coughing spell, feeling as if she cannot catch her breath, and as if she is about to lose contact. The coughing spell is associated with muscle movement artifact, followed by burst of high amplitude delta. The heart rate increases to 132 beats per minute.
By 11:31:44: the EEG has returned to normal, but the patient remains tachycardic and feels unwell. Additional coughing again produces some of the same artifact, and some burst of delta.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response. HR: 	84-132 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The rhythmic mid temporal theta described above is a normal variant, sometimes referred to as psychomotor variant. The patient had 2 episodes of coughing, with an increase in delta. The physiologic conclusion would be that prolonged coughing is the results in a hyperventilation response with the same sort of entity as would be expected to see in hyperventilation in the lab.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:   58 year-old male with multiple motor vehicle accidents, left temporoparietal  craniotomy  with a plate. Patient was having episodes shortly after his second head trauma in December 2007 when he had episodic dizziness, double vision and drop attacks. Now, resolving post traumatic symptoms.
MEDICATIONS:   Lisinopril
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are preformed. This is a 1 hour Sleep-Deprived EEG. Left craniotomy defect is observed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz posterior dominant rhythm. A prominent craniotomy defect is observed with wicked from the left central temporal region. Underneath the wicked, there is a small amount of slow delta. Hyperventilation is performed  early on in the record accentuating the focal slowing. This is followed by drowsiness  with slow rolling eye movements. Vertex waves are observed in stage 1 sleep followed by arousals. Possible REM sleep is observed in this record in the sleep deprived 1 hour record with a characteristic  theta and lateral eye movements in a past who does not appear to be awake. This may have been associated with an arousal. An EMG monitor was not employed. In the extended sleep recording, there is vertex activity. There is alpha frequency activity picked up on the left more so that the right into stage 2 sleep which is an unusual finding in that is it sometimes seen on the right would not be considered a clearly pathological entity. Photic stimulation elicits brief bilateral driving.
HR: 	54 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	Intermittent focal slowing particularly observed in drowsiness in the left central temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are a number of unusual features in this record including the possibility of REM sleep in a single 1 hour record. The REM sleep appeared to be fragmented.  Another usual feature was the presence of rhythmic alpha rhythmic activity from the left central temporal region into stage 2 sleep.
This could not be considered clearly pathological  as it was sometimes present on there right. In any case, the alpha frequency activity did not wax and wane as might be anticipated in an epileptiform  pathology
Given the presence of the metal plate, epileptiform  activity may be under recognized in this individual. The previous craniotomy and skull defect in this case provide a breech rhythm with accentuation of activity, but the possibility of that activity is masked could not be excluded. This individual did not experience any other his paroxysmal spells during the study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due to 1. Intermittent focal slowing particularly observed in drowsiness in the left central temporal region.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old right handed male with epilepsy since 2007, breakthrough seizure 2 weeks ago with loss of consciousness and confusion. This is an outpatient EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm and a small amount of low-voltage frontocentral beta activity. Hyperventilation is performed early on in the record, producing and increase in amplitude of the background as well as some rhythmic delta from the right hemisphere, but without disruption of the underlying faster frequency activity. As the patient becomes drowsy again, there is a subtle disruption of faster frequency activity with subtle rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region. This is seen with brief transitions into stage II sleep but deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. On one occasion, in the transition to sleep there are sharp waves with rhythmic slowing out of the right temporal region followed by an arousal period. Unfortunately, there is some wick-like activity at this same time and there are some additional more subtle sharp waves without the same faster frequency activity noted. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response. During photic stimulation, a well defined right anterotemporal spike in slow-wave complex is observed. Additional spike complexes are noted at the very end of the record, again right anterotemporal.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region.
2. Right anterotemporal spike and slow-wave complexes and sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings support a localization related mechanism for epilepsy.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to 1. Rhythmic slowing in the right temporal region. 2. Right anterotemporal spike and slow-wave complexes and sharp waves.

Generalized background slowing.
An asymmetry with more significant arrhythmic delta activity and more slowing on the right.
Occasional right frontal sharp waves are sharply contoured transients in the context of right frontal central focal slowing.

10-20 system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically
satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG  and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 8.3 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.  Maximal
wakefulness on the whole is relatively symmetric




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.  Focal slowing is noted in drowsiness
with dropout of faster frequency activity in the right hemisphere compared to the left




Sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.  Stage II sleep also includes some focality and
sleep morphologies are better developed on the left



Mild generalized slowing is present.

In drowsiness and sleep focal slowing is present on the right



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None




ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Photic Stimulation: Driving responses elicited, better on the left



EVENTS:

There are  no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 72 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:

1.  Focal slowing in the right hemisphere noted in drowsiness and sleep



CLINICAL CORRELATION:



No epileptiform features were identified.  These study may be compared to previous studies,
particularly in view of the patient's cerebrovascular disease.




Attending Epileptologist: 

I have personally reviewed this study, and this report represents my findings and conclusions.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 
1.  Focal slowing in the right hemisphere noted in drowsiness and sleep

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year-old mentally retarded male admitted with aspiration
pneumonia and tonoclonic seizures at an unknown time.
MEDICATIONS: Lovenox, Zosyn, Azithromycin, Lorazepam, Tegretol, Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG is performed in laboratory using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the patient is awake with a
well organized, 10.5 Hertz, 30 mcv posterior dominant rhythm in a generous amount of
low voltage, frontal central theta activity. The patient is noted to have a fair amount of
snore artifact as he drifts off to sleep. Vertex waves are observed in stage I sleep,
followed by arousals. Snore and muscle artifact obscure the right temporal electrodes
as the patient drifts off into sleep. Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is
transitioning to and from stage II sleep. Despite this, both the photic driving and a
photoelectric artifact is observed.
HR: 96 bpm.
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive focal or epileptiform features were seen,
however, the muscle artifact on the right was a concern. Given this individual has a
history of obstructive sleep apnea or snoring, an additional evaluation may be
appropriate.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with developmental disability and epilepsy.  Three seizures per month, last October 18th.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, lovastatin, Norvasc, others.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Hyperventilation was attempted, but not completed at the patient's request.  Photic stimulation was completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  The waking background is intermittently interrupted by rhythmic theta which can be diffuse, frontocentral bilateral.  There are also shifting asymmetries noted.  The patient transitions rapidly in and out of stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  In the transition in and out of sleep, rare mu activity was identified.  There is also some sharply contoured slowing in the frontocentral regions bilaterally.

Photic stimulation is performed as the patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep.  Scant driving was noted.  Heart rate 84 BPM with occasional PVCs.

IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Intermittent excess theta.
2. Mild background disorganization.
3. Occasional bursts of frontally predominant sharply contoured slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This individual had difficult relaxing during the study.  If additional information is needed to localize this patient's epilepsy, a more prolonged sleep study may be considered.  Additional evaluation for this patient's PVCs may be warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to 1. Intermittent excess theta. 2. Mild background disorganization. 3. Occasional bursts of frontally predominant sharply contoured slowing.

report:

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm. IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This EEG is worrisome in that there a handful of discharges which resemble a normal variant, but have a slightly slower periodicity and although they have a typical morphology, occur at frequency of 3.6 hertz and would suggest a left temporal focus.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	65 year-old right-handed gentleman  with epilepsy since 2006. Last seizure, August 2007. Seizures described as staring spells with unawareness for
10 minutes followed by confusion. Past history of left temporal brain tumor.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. The amplitude from the right is higher amplitude than the left. Wicket activity is observed. Features of drowsiness include anterior spread of the alpha rhythm. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous bilateral driving. HR: 	50-60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORR ELATION:
Despite the history of a brain tumor, no definitive focal nor
epileptiform features were observed. The amplitude asymmetry described above is within no malignancy  is within normal range. Interestingly, for an individual with a history of a brain tumor the technologist did not observe a craniotomy defect.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY: 	This is a 65-year-old male with adult-onset generalized tonic­ clonic seizures and episode of spacing out and decline of cognitive function for the last few months and a questionable of brain tumor at an outside hospital.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal, Norvasc.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION  OF THE RECORD: 	In the wakefulness, the background showed intermittent alpha rhythm with 6.5 to 7 Hz when the patient is in the relaxed position, otherwise the background showed a lot of artifacts due to patient's anxiety and tension. An occasional Wicket activity noticed as well.  There was subtle right focal slowing and possible right temporal sharps which seemed to be sitting with the eye movements artifact.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record, and photic stimulation did not show any drive response.
HR: 	40 bpm
IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due :
1.  Generalized  background slowing.
2. Subtle right focal slowing.
3.  Possible right temporal sharps.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: Focal slowing and sharp waves support localization related epilepsy. The background slowing is not specific which could represent an effect from the Trileptal medication as the patient had previous normal EEG. Other considerations include post-ictal state or a diffuse disorder of cerebral function such as dementia.  Clinical correlation is warranted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:   Abnormal EEG due  1.  Generalized  background slowing. 2. Subtle right focal slowing. 3.  Possible right temporal sharps.

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.

2. 	Periodic discharges seen with the left greater than right maximum which occasionally occurs on the record.

report:
History:	28 year old female with a history of epilepsy. Patient had 3 seizures on 6/16/14.
Patient is currently pregnant.
Medications:	Lamotrigine
Sedation:
EEG Type:	Awake & asleep
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric
Continuous polymorphic theta and delta activity is present in the right temporooccipital region
during wakefulness, increasing during drowsiness.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
induces symmetric photic driving at multiple flash rates.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, continuous, mild, right, temporooccipital
No epileptiform discharges
Sleep, stage 2
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep  23-minute EEG due to continuous focal slowing in the
right temporooccipital region.  This finding is indicative of a focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly
structural in etiology.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a
clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and asleep  23-minute EEG due to continuous focal slowing in the
right temporooccipital region.  This finding is indicative of a focal cerebral dysfunction, possibly
structural in etiology.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a
clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old lady with past medical history of subarachnoid hemorrhage in 2007, status post hypertension and asthma and also history of seizures with left-sided weakness secondary to old stroke, presents for episodes of stuttering speech and right upper extremity shaking.
MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, Norvasc, Prozac, Prilosec, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm was 9-10 Hz in frequency 30-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity, which is distributed symmetrically.  Stage 1 and stage 2 sleep are characterized by disappearance of the alpha rhythm and slowing of the background and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact, and presence of posts, K complexes, vertex sharp transients, and sleep spindles.  There are also intermittent bursts of bitemporal slowing at F7/T3 and F8/T4 lasting for 1-2 seconds.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies, and results in a symmetric driving response.  Hyperventilation was performed and resulted in slowing of the background activity.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to bitemporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Bitemporal slowing is suggestive of bilateral structural abnormalities or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures are captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures. If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG or continuous bedside EEG or ambulatory, an EEG monitoring maybe helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to bitemporal slowing.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were identified in this record.

report:

INTRODUCTION:  Extended, digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  The patient was somewhat symptomatic during the EEG, reporting disequilibrium.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the EEG demonstrates an awake pattern with a symmetric reactive alpha rhythm.  This is disrupted by intermittent bursts of rhythmic right temporal delta with admixed sharp waves.  The bursts of sharp waves and delta are on the order of 5-10-15 seconds in duration.  No alteration in the patient's motor or sensory symptoms were seen in association with these discharges.  The patient's responses are slowed, but the tech who spends 40 minutes with the patient, finds that the patient's responsiveness is not so significantly different than the sections of the record without the bursts.  As the recording concludes, the epileptiform activity is decreasing, but there remains some rhythmic right temporal slowing.  The sharp waves are significantly more discreet.
Photic stimulation was performed at the end of the record.  A driving response was identified.  In the final minutes of the recording, another more brief burst of right temporal sharp waves was noted.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Well-defined high amplitude right temporal sharp waves.
Bursts of rhythmic temporal theta.
Bursts of rhythmic slowing and sharp waves lasting between 5 and 13 seconds without significant change in the patient's clinical status.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings suggest a highly irritative focus.  This may be a postictal study, but ongoing vigilance is essential (the patient was admitted to the hospital based on this result).
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to Well-defined high amplitude right temporal sharp waves. Bursts of rhythmic temporal theta. Bursts of rhythmic slowing and sharp waves lasting between 5 and 13 seconds without significant change in the patient's clinical status.

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 11 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.




Diffuse excess beta activity is present.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.







EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

A single brief burst (~1.5 seconds) of high amplitude ~2.5 Hz generalized frontally predominant
moderate-to-high amplitude polyspikes is captured towards the end of the recording during stage II
sleep.




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None

Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is performed for 180 seconds with good cooperation and produces
no effect.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving, which is a normal finding.



EVENTS:

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.



IMPRESSION:

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:


1. A single brief burst of high amplitude ~2.5 Hz generalized frontally predominant moderate-to-high
amplitude polyspikes is captured during stage II sleep.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

This finding is suggestive of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.



Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or
barbiturates.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 
This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 

1. A single brief burst of high amplitude ~2.5 Hz generalized frontally predominant moderate-to-high
amplitude polyspikes is captured during stage II sleep.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 65-year-old gentleman with history of COPD, hypertension, diabetes, tooth cancer, status post treatment, who presents with left focal seizures described as a left arm shaking lasting for a few minutes, resolved by administration of Ativan 2 mg IV.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-7.5 Hz in frequency, well-formed on the left side, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 5-7 Hz diffuse theta activity noted during wakefulness.  There is attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the right hemisphere, most pronounced in posterior quadrant with intermittent slowing in the left cerebral hemisphere.  The lethargic state is characterized by further slowing of the background and disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm.  Heart rate was 90 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness.
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies and also slowing in the left posterior quadrant.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings are suggestive of either metabolic, toxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medication or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies in the left cerebral hemisphere is likely due to the patient's history of stroke.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures is captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION This is an abnormal EEG recording due to Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness. Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm. Attenuation and loss of faster frequencies and also slowing in the left posterior quadrant.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  51 year old right handed gentleman with history of heroine addiction, one year history of palpitations, numbness right arm and leg, intermittent loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS:  Clonidine.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There are occasional bursts of shifting slowing, particularly in the right central region.  Wicket activity is noted, particularly on the left. Features of drowsiness include an increase in theta.  Vertex waves and spindles are noted in stage II sleep.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in rhythmic slowing.   Photic stimulation is performed while the patient is transitioning in and out of stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles, and POSTS. There are rare, right central sharp waves noted, as well as a single posteriorly predominant spike at P4.  There are really only the two C4 spikes and the posterior spike.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Shifting slowing, a little bit more so on the right central region on the left.
Two right central and one occipital, right greater than left, sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The sharp waves are in the region of this patient's cerebrovascular disease.  The shifting slowing is a nonspecific finding which can be
seen in the context of underlying ischemic cerebrovascular disease.  Overall, this was otherwise a sharply contoured, but otherwise unremarkable background.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to Shifting slowing, a little bit more so on the right central region on the left. Two right central and one occipital, right greater than left, sharp waves.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with traumatic brain injury, failure to thrive, status post PEG and trach.  The patient now awake and alert after multiple seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Trileptal.  Others, metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20 minute digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is quite fragile, but awake.  He is responsive to questions.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The right hemisphere is low voltage and relatively featureless.  The left hemisphere is remarkable for a craniotomy defect, but also periodic, high amplitude delta activity with a left central parietal spike and wave complex.  The spike and wave complex is periodic in nature and has the periodicity of about 8 per 10 seconds.  There is a small amount of waxing and waning of the epileptiform discharge, but no clear ictal pattern.  Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in theta in the left hemisphere as well as eye movement.
Heart rate:  80 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
A continuous periodic discharge, which includes a spike as well as periodic delta from the left hemisphere, maximum in the central parietal region.
Markedly slow and suppressed pattern from the right with volume conduction of the epileptiform discharge on the left to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The patient seems to be awake and interactive despite the discharge described above.  In addition, stimulation of the patient clearly produces an alerting response on top of the periodic complex.  The discharge described above may be a chronic finding or a post-ictal finding, but does not appear to be to be a true seizure.   Ongoing vigilance is suggested. No clinical seizures noted at this time.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to A continuous periodic discharge, which includes a spike as well as periodic delta from the left hemisphere, maximum in the central parietal region. Markedly slow and suppressed pattern from the right with volume conduction of the epileptiform discharge on the left to the right.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 61-year-old male with epilepsy.  Has complex neurosurgical history including traumatic brain injury, subarachnoid hemorrhage, subdural hematoma, aphagia, skull defect, and past left-sided edema.  Past history of recurrent seizures in July 2014, recently admitted to the hospital in February 2015.  No recent reported seizures, but previous status epilepticus and pleds from the left.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, atorvastatin, Keppra, metoprolol, phenobarbital, and Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  A 20-minute digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  This is a technically acceptable EEG with acceptable impedances, although there is a prominent craniotomy defect.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background from the right hemisphere includes a low voltage, continuous, primarily beta frequency pattern.  The left hemisphere demonstrates a prominent breach rhythm.  There are bursts of rhythmic 3 to 4 Hz activity of 1 to 3 seconds duration.  Some of these are associated with a sharp waves.  The bursts of rhythmic slowing with left mid temporal sharp waves are more prominent as the patient became drowsy.
Heart rate: 54 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
A marked interhemispheric asymmetry.
A low voltage slow pattern from the right with primarily beta frequency activity.
A pattern from the left with higher amplitude delta, a prominent reach, and a left mid temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is one of many EEGs for this adult, who has been evaluated for status epilepticus and seizures.  The epileptiform activity today is primarily left mid temporal, which in some ways is similar to the continuous EEG monitoring.  A contrast to February 2015 EEG monitor, which identified epileptiform activity from the left hemisphere, but that epileptiform activity was much more prominent in the central parietal region.
This EEG continues to support a focal mechanism for this patient's seizures.  The epileptiform activity is in the region of the patient's head trauma.  The bilateral background slowing supports a severe disturbance of cerebral function.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to A marked interhemispheric asymmetry. A low voltage slow pattern from the right with primarily beta frequency activity. A pattern from the left with higher amplitude delta, a prominent reach, and a left mid temporal sharp waves.

Tactile stimulation of the patient produces an arousal response with a glimpse of a 10 Hz alpha rhythm on the right and more of a theta pattern on the left.  The patient then returns to a drowsy state.
Heart rate 96 BPM
IMPRESSION:
Abnormal EEG due to continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere.
Sharply contoured delta from the left maximum mid temporal.
Continuous
Mild slowing on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is supportive of a structural or functional process on the left.  For this patient with recurrent status epilepticus, this record demonstrates an ongoing irritative process.  This EEG is similar to previous studies of April 2015.

IMPRESSION Abnormal EEG due to continuous focal slowing from the left hemisphere. Sharply contoured delta from the left maximum mid temporal. Continuous
Mild slowing on the right.

report:
REASON FOR STUDY:  Recurrent seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman with Lyme disease, gastroparesis, episodes of staring spells and confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Toradol, oxycodone, Lovenox, Protonix.
INTRODUCTION:  A long-term EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Continuous spike wave detection as well as seizure detection software along the patient's alarm events as well as nurses notes were used to review the EEG.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  Some electrode artifact during the episodes as described below.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta.  Activating procedures were not performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EVENTS:  The patient had 3 events during the admission.  The first one occurred at 7:00 p.m. after the doctor asked her to raise and lower her hands, and breathe heavily.  The patient started complaining of a headache, later ringing in the ears and became unresponsive with the eyes twitching and rolling backwards with forced eye closure, and some trembling.  The patient also had complaints of some right-sided numbness before the episode started.  The patient remained unresponsive to verbal motor commands until about 7:06:28 p.m.  She had a second event at 8:53:40 p.m. with a similar presentation of eyes rolling back and becoming unresponsive to verbal commands, and then trembling lasting until 8:58 p.m.  At the end she cried just as she did in the first event.  Then she had a third event occurring at 9:53:08 p.m. lasting until 9:58:47 p.m. again with eye fluttering,  trembling and following commands, and afterwards crying.  During all 3 events even though the last 1 there was some substantial electrode artifact and muscle artifact there was no clear EEG changes.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and sleep EEG.  The 3 episodes which were described above had no EEG correlate and clinically appeared to be consistent with her typical spells.  The lack of any EEG abnormalities during the event is diagnostic of a psychogenic nonepileptic event.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and sleep EEG.

report:
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 19-year-old woman with gastroparesis, staring spells, and confusion.  History of seizures with aura of headache, lightheadedness, ringing in her ears, and loss of vision.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a somewhat unusual background.  There are sections of the record with some 5-6 Hz posteriorly predominant activity with a 9 Hz mu rhythm.  The posterior dominant activity is slow, notched, and somewhat regular, suggesting that there may be an underlying somewhat irregular alpha subharmonic.  Prominent lambda confounds this picture.  Features of drowsiness include slow rolling eye movements.  The somewhat notched posterior predominant pattern is seen when the patient is awake, as well as she starts to drift into drowsiness.
Hyperventilation seems to accentuate underlying, posteriorly predominant slowing.
Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response.
Heart rate:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This must be considered an abnormal EEG due to:  Somewhat slow irregular theta frequency activity in the posterior regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Harmonic since subharmonics are normal findings, but there is clearly irregular posteriorly predominant theta that cannot be considered a normal variant.  This EEG differs from a previous EEG on January 4, 2013 which was a normal routine study.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This must be considered an abnormal EEG due to:  Somewhat slow irregular theta frequency activity in the posterior regions.

report:
History:	69 year old man with focal seizures. Medications:	Keppra, Dilantin, Phenobarbital Sedation:
EEG Type:	Continuous (inpt, video), 24 hrs
Technique:		International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG electrodes, awake, drowsy
Continuous bedside video-EEG  monitoring
Continuous EEG monitoring was performed for 24 hours from 08/26/2015 till 08/27/2015.    Nursing­ initiated event buttons were correlated with clinical behavior.  Ongoing raw EEG data was reviewed at least twice daily by the EEG team for detection of seizures and changes in EEG patterns.   All automatically detected events were reviewed in detail by the attending neurologist.
# Push button events
Description of pushbutton events
Description:
There is no clear PDR or AP gradient while the patient is awake. The awake background consists of a mixture of a low amplitude beta>theta activity with theta activity most pronounced over the left frontotemporal region. As the recording progresses, the background becomes more attenuated- this corresponds to initiation  of phenobarbital. Additional underriding fast activity is captured over the left anterior quadrant. Diffuse excess beta activity is seen. Continuous high amplitude rhythmic and semi­ rhythmic (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs) up to 1 Hz sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves emanate from
the left anterior quadrant, most prominent over the F3 lead. Starting at -8:27 AM, intermittent left anterior quadrant seizures appear. They last - 25-60 seconds and have no clinical correlate. They occur at variable frequency throughout the recording, up to multiple times per hour (between 4-5 PM), ie, frank focal status epilepticus. Last clear seizure is captured at -2:07 AM. Electrographically, seizures start with rhythmic left anterior delta- theta activity that rapidly increases in amplitude and rhythmicity, decreases in frequency and spreads throughout the left hemisphere. Periods of brief background discontinuity and sleep-spindle-like waveforms (more visible over the left) are seen during sleep.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, left anterior, variable frequency , last @2:07 am Status epilepticus , left anterior, between - 4-5 PM
PEDs (periodic epileptiform discharges), left anterior Pseudoperiodic discharges, left anterior
Beta, excessive
Attenuation , due to phenobarbital initiation
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL continuous video -24 hour EEG due to continuous left anterior periodic and semi periodic epileptiform discharges (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), left anterior quadrant focal seizures and brief focal status epilepticus, left anterior focal slowing and diffuse slowing . There is a focal structural epileptogenic lesion in the left anterior quadrant.  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific. Breach rhythm is secondary to the skull defect. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
These findings were conveyed to the primary team and medication regimen was adjusted (phenobarbital was added).
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL continuous video -24 hour EEG due to continuous left anterior periodic and semi periodic epileptiform discharges (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), left anterior quadrant focal seizures and brief focal status epilepticus, left anterior focal slowing and diffuse slowing . There is a focal structural epileptogenic lesion in the left anterior quadrant.  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific. Breach rhythm is secondary to the skull defect. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

The awake background consists of a mixture of a low amplitude beta>theta activity with theta activity most pronounced over the left frontotemporal region. As the recording progresses, the background becomes more attenuated- this corresponds to initiation  of phenobarbital. Additional underriding fast activity is captured over the left anterior quadrant. Diffuse excess beta activity is seen. Continuous high amplitude rhythmic and semi­ rhythmic (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs) up to 1 Hz sharp waves with aftergoing slow waves emanate from
the left anterior quadrant, most prominent over the F3 lead. Starting at -8:27 AM, intermittent left anterior quadrant seizures appear. They last - 25-60 seconds and have no clinical correlate. They occur at variable frequency throughout the recording, up to multiple times per hour (between 4-5 PM), ie, frank focal status epilepticus. Last clear seizure is captured at -2:07 AM. Electrographically, seizures start with rhythmic left anterior delta- theta activity that rapidly increases in amplitude and rhythmicity, decreases in frequency and spreads throughout the left hemisphere. Periods of brief background discontinuity and sleep-spindle-like waveforms (more visible over the left) are seen during sleep.
Summary of Findings:
Seizure, left anterior, variable frequency , last @2:07 am Status epilepticus , left anterior, between - 4-5 PM
PEDs (periodic epileptiform discharges), left anterior Pseudoperiodic discharges, left anterior
Beta, excessive
Attenuation , due to phenobarbital initiation
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL continuous video -24 hour EEG due to continuous left anterior periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), left anterior quadrant focal seizures and brief focal status epilepticus, left anterior focal slowing and diffuse slowing . There is a focal structural epileptogenic lesion in the left anterior quadrant.  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific. Breach rhythm is secondary to the skull defect. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
These findings were conveyed to the primary team and medication regimen was adjusted (phenobarbital was added).
IMPRESSION: Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL continuous video -24 hour EEG due to continuous left anterior periodic and periodic epileptiform discharges (PLEDs and quasi-PLEDs), left anterior quadrant focal seizures and brief focal status epilepticus, left anterior focal slowing and diffuse slowing . There is a focal structural epileptogenic lesion in the left anterior quadrant.  Diffuse slowing is indicative of mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is etiologically nonspecific. Breach rhythm is secondary to the skull defect. Excessive beta activity could be secondary to the medication effect, such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates

report:
AGE: 69 y.o.
SEX: male
DATE OF STUDY: 11/03/2015
RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: inpatient
EEG TYPE: 40-60 min, awake and drowsy EEG #: 15-1620
HISTORY:
69 y.o. male with a history of metastatic brain cancer (adenocarcinoma of unknown origin, s/p L craniotomy and radiation therapy) referred for routine EEG for	management of seizure exacerbation.
MEDICATIONS:
Home Regimen: Keppra 1500 mg q12h
Received Ativan 8 mg prior to this study and additional Keppra 1500 mg
SEDATION: Ativan as above TECHNIQUE:
A 21 channel electroencephalogram	(EEG) was recorded using the
International 10-20 system with Tl/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and included a single channel of EKG.
EEG BACKGROUND:
The study opens to a background that is continuous, asymmetric, and poorly organized.
The right hemisphere consists of a disorganized mixture of delta with admixed theta and beta.
The left hemisphere consists of a disorganized mixture of delta,
theta, alpha, and beta. There are waveforms of higher amplitude and admixed faster frequencies noted over the left hemisphere, maximum over the fronto-temporal region (Fpl, F7).
The background is reactive.	As the study progresses, fragments of an irregular posterior dominant rhythm of 8 Hz, better seen over the right hemisphere, become apparent.
Sleep transients are not captured.
There is mild to moderate generalized slowing, improving to mild over the study.
There is continuous left hemispheric (fronto-temporal max) polymorphic slowing.
EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:
1. Continuous 1-1.5 Hz sharp-and-slow-wave discharges, left frontotemporal maximum (max F7, T3, F3, C3; also known as lateralized periodic discharges, LPDs) . Occasionally these fluctuate in frequency, occurring at up to 3 Hz for periods <2 seconds, without clear evolution. Examples occur at 08:40, 08:57, 08:58, the fluctuations persist up to 1 min and 25 sec. There is no clinical correlate.
OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):
None
ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
EVENTS:
There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.
HEART RATE:
A heart rate of 78 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.
IMPRESSION:
This is an abnormal awake and drowsy routine EEG due to:
Mild to moderate generalized slowing, which improves to mild over the course of the recording, with suboptimal organization
Continuous left hemispheric (fronto-temporal max) polymorphic slowing
Waveforms of higher amplitude and admixed faster frequencies noted over the left hemisphere, maximum over the fronto-temporal region (Fpl, F7), likely representing breach rhythm
Continuous left fronto-temporal lateralized periodic discharges that occasionally fluctuate
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
These findings indicate the presence of highly epileptogenic discharges over the left fronto-temporal region, superimposed on left hemisphere dysfunction that is likely structural in etiology. There is additionally mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which improves over the course of the recording to "mild." A left fronto-temporal breach rhythm is consistent with
this patient' s known history of craniotomy .
No definite electrographic seizures were - captured.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION This is an abnormal awake and drowsy routine EEG due to Mild to moderate generalized slowing, which improves to mild over the course of the recording, with suboptimal organization
Continuous left hemispheric (fronto-temporal max) polymorphic slowing
Waveforms of higher amplitude and admixed faster frequencies noted over the left hemisphere, maximum over the fronto-temporal region (Fpl, F7), likely representing breach rhythm
Continuous left fronto-temporal lateralized periodic discharges that occasionally fluctuate

report:
History:	35 year old man with a history of seizures since 1999 after a gun shot wound behind

left year.  Most recent seizure occurred ~ 2 weeks ago.

Medications:	Tegretol, Keppra

Sedation:

EEG Type:	Awake & asleep

Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG

electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, hyperventilation, photic

Description:

Brief waking background is characterized by low voltage Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates

symmetrically with eye opening.  Fast alpha variant is observed.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz

activity is present, maximal over bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows

to central theta activity, frontal beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm

attenuates and becomes intermittent.  During stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate

voltage 2-4Hz activity, and symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.

No focal slowing is present.  Intrusions of polymorphic theta and delta activity are seen during brief

wakefulness.  Similar theta and delta activity is noted during sleep.  No epileptiform discharges are

present.

Hyperventilation is performed for 240 seconds with fair cooperation, and patient falls asleep.

Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces symmetric photic driving at

multiple flash rates.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION:  A 1-hour digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient was quite somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the overall EEG is low voltage with generous beta.  Scant alpha rhythm was identified.  In this low voltage record, in hyperventilation and drowsiness, there is a subtle, low voltage infrequent somewhat irregular, left temporal slowing.  In addition, there are rare bursts of focal slowing from the right temporal region noted following hyperventilation.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta, followed by vertex waves and K complexes, as well as spindles.
Notable findings in this record include a brief burst of slower, rhythmic 3 hertz delta activity from the left temporal region.  This is followed by a single, low voltage, left temporal sharp waves.  These findings are best visualized in an average reference.
Photic stimulation elicited bilateral driving.  Hyperventilation as described above.  Heart rate slightly irregular 90bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to:
A single, well demarcated burst of rhythmic left temporal slowing.
Very infrequent bursts of shifting lower voltage, temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Only, a single sharp wave was noted in this record.  In this particular clinical context, however, the single sharp waves may be considered as part of this patient's pathology.  No well-defined, higher amplitude spike and slow wave and sharp and slow wave complexes were noted.
IMPRESSION: IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to A single, well demarcated burst of rhythmic left temporal slowing. Very infrequent bursts of shifting lower voltage, temporal slowing.

report:
History:	66 year old woman with a history of nocturnal seizures.
Medications:	Keppra, Ropinirole, Baclofen, Atenolol, Plavix.
Sedation:	None
EEG Type:	Extended, 40-60 min
Technique:	International 10-20 System; standard 21 electrodes with T1/T2 electrodes and EKG
electrodes, awake, drowsy, asleep, photic
Description:
Waking background is characterized by a 25-40uV, 10Hz alpha rhythm, which attenuates
symmetrically with eye opening.  Symmetric 5-15uV, 18-25Hz activity is present, maximal over
bilateral frontal regions.  During drowsiness, the background slows to central theta activity, frontal
beta activity becomes more prominent, and the alpha rhythm attenuates and becomes intermittent.
During brief stage 2 sleep, the record slows further to moderate voltage 2-4Hz activity, and
symmetric sleep spindles and K complexes appear.
Occasional polymorphic delta activity is observed over the left anterior temporal region, increasing
during drowsiness.  No epileptiform discharges are present.
Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps)
does not produce additional abnormalities.  A single EKG lead demonstrates heart rate of <60 bpm.
Summary of Findings:
Focal slowing, polymorphic, occasional, moderate, left temporal, anterior
Sleep, stage 2, brief
No epileptiform discharges
Interpretation:
This is an ABNORMAL awake and briefly asleep 1 hour EEG due to occasional moderate left
anterior temporal focal slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a
routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.
IMPRESSION:
Interpretation This is an ABNORMAL awake and briefly asleep 1 hour EEG due to occasional moderate left
anterior temporal focal slowing. This finding is indicative of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is
etiologically non-specific, but possibly structural in origin.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a
routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy

report:
HISTORY:

91 y.o. female with a history of epilepsy after recent CVA, now with waxing and
waning MSE referred for routine EEG for assessment of mental status change.



MEDICATIONS:

Previously on LEV, now receiving VPA.




SEDATION: Ativan during the EEG for seizure



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a  technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and verbal  stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:







As the study begins, patient is awake. The waking background is characterized by the presence of a
symmetric mixture of 4 Hz theta frequencies, with scant reactive 6 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present. There is a lot
of muscle and chew artifact and frontal beta.  The patient is demonstrates psychomotor slowing




A burst of frontal fast activity is followed by R temporal ADA and then sharp waves. The discharge
may have started before the EEG began but it is seen  At 10:39. When tested,  the patient has
speech arrest. She received 2 mg Ativan and afterwards, the EEG pattern shifts to symmetric theta,
with prominent delta, and the patient's speech returned.



Generalized slowing is present.

Shiftting  focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:R temporal sharp waves



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

Sharpy contoured activity and FIRDA



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES: tactile stimulation elicits an increase in theta


EVENTS:


There was one  clinical / electrographic event captured during this study.  See above


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 96 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to:

1. Clinical seizures, with challenging EEG correlate, but likely from the right.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:

These findings are suggestive of an ictal process as a contributor to the confusion described by the
family.  Although the seizure was characterized by speech arrest, it seems to arise from the right.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake and drowsy  routine EEG due to 
1. Clinical seizures, with challenging EEG correlate, but likely from the right.

report:
HISTORY:

92 y.o. female with a history of recurrent strokelike symptoms.  Admitted with
waxing and waning mental status.  Had an episode of speech arrest during baseline EEG with right
rhythmic discharge referred for EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Keppra was discontinued and the patient received Depakote

TECHNIQUE:

T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record and
included a single channel of EKG and verbal stimulation.  The patient was initially very drowsy after
receiving Ativan.  As the recording continued, she had difficulty keeping electrodes on and was
asking to have the study discontinued on the morning of the 16th




.


DAY 1 (05-15-16,  - 5/16/2016,)



BACKGROUND:

Although initially, the patient is very sedated, the initial awake record demonstrated  continuous,
symmetric, well-organized EEG , and consists predominantly of theta with admixed frontocentral beta
.


Posterior dominant rhythm was minimal



The background is   Reactive and  variable.



There were  no persistent asymmetries in amplitude and frequency.


Sleep was was characterized by vertex waves.



PAROXSYMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

none


EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

none

EVENTS: no clinical seizures.  Intermittent slow speech was not associated



EKG: A single lead captured HR 60 BPM

Although the baseline EEG demonstrated rhythmic slowing from the right temporal region which was
sharply contoured with underlying sharp waves, this study shows only generalized background slowing.

This is abnormal video EEG due to:



1. generalized background slowing-

These findings support a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral dysfunction.  These findings may be

Although the patient had a clear, clinical seizure in the EEG lab which may have started before the
EEG was running, no additional seizures were noted.


She did receive neurological medications which may have contributed to the psychomotor slowing
noted on the morning of the 16th

GABAPENTIN

TECHNIQUE:

A  Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is symmetric, reactive, and consists of a mixture of alpha and a moderate
amount of bifrontal beta activity, organized in a normal anterior-to-posterior gradient.  Wakefulness is
characterized by a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm (PDR), which
attenuates symmetrically with eye opening.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.




Sleep is not captured

No epileptiform activity is present.

None

Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.


Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) does not produce
any EEG changes.

There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.

A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.

reported or detected.

This is a normal awake and drowsy  routine EEG.

report:
DATE OF STUDY: 09/12/16

RECORDING ENVIRONMENT: outpatient


EEG TYPE: 60 min +, awake and asleep




HISTORY:

a 58 y.o. male with a history of liver disease and seizures referred for routine
1hour  EEG for characterization of seizures.



MEDICATIONS:


Current Outpatient Prescriptions:

OXcarbazepine (TRILEPTAL) 150 mg tablet, Take 2 tablets by mouth 2 times daily. Take as directed

gabapentin (NEURONTIN) 600 mg tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth 4 times daily (before meals and
nightly) for 360 days.


NALTREXONE MICROSPHERES (VIVITROL IM), Inject  into the muscle every 30 days.


METOPROLOL SUCCINATE (TOPROL XL PO), Take 50 mg by mouth daily.

omeprazole (PRILOSEC) 20 mg capsule, 2 times daily.

nortriptyline (PAMELOR) 25 mg capsule, Take  by mouth nightly.



No current facility-administered medications for this visit.






SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:


A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically  satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.



EEG BACKGROUND:

The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 8.5-9 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present. Lambda is
seen. Likely Mu was noted, but no testing was done to confirm this.





During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with abundant POSTS synchronous and symmetric
vertex waves, sleep spindles and K-complexes. Slow wave sleep was not captured.



Intermittent  slowing is present, characterized by a slow alpha of 7.8-8.3 Hz.

No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

None



OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):

None



ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:


Photic Stimulation: scant driving present



EVENTS:

There are  no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.



HEART RATE:

A heart rate of 78 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.





IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to:

1. Intermittent, mild background slowing in a very somnolent patient.



CLINICAL CORRELATION:


These findings are non specific and could be related to medicines or liver disease. There were no
sharp waves.
IMPRESSION:
IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake and asleep routine EEG due to 
1. Intermittent, mild background slowing in a very somnolent patient.

EEG TYPE: 40-60 min, awake and asleep




HISTORY:

a 20 y.o. male with a history of intellectual disability, autism and epilepsy referred
for routine EEG for evaluation of paroxysmal events (staring)



MEDICATIONS:


multivitamin (THERAGRAN) per tablet, Take 1 tablet by mouth daily.


SEDATION: None



TECHNIQUE:

A Digital Video 21 channel electroencephalogram (EEG) was recorded using the International 10-20
system with T1/T2 electrodes and utilized a NicOne system. This was a technically satisfactory record
and included a single channel of EKG and photic stimulation.




EEG BACKGROUND:







The waking background is characterized by the presence of a well organized symmetric mixture of
alpha and beta frequencies, with a symmetric and reactive 10 Hertz posterior dominant rhythm
(PDR). The normal anterior-to-posterior gradient of frequency and amplitude is present.




During drowsiness, slow rolling eye movements, attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior
dominant rhythm, and diffuse background slowing are seen.



Sleep is characterized by normal sleep transients, with synchronous and symmetric vertex waves,
sleep spindles and K-complexes.



No generalized slowing is present.

No focal slowing is present.



EPILEPTIFORM ACTIVITY:

1. Occasional (1/hour to <1min) 1-2.5 second bursts of 3.5-5 Hz generalized (mostly frontally-
predominant but rarely occipitally-predominant) irregular spike- and polyspike-and-wave activity, in
wake and sleep. In sleep they tend to superimpose on K-complexes (dyshormia). There is no clear
clinical correlate but patient is not tested during them.




OTHER PAROXYSMAL ACTIVITY (NON-EPILEPTIFORM):


None


ACTIVATION PROCEDURES:



Hyperventilation: Hyperventilation is not performed.



Photic Stimulation: Stepped photic stimulation from 1-21 flashes per second (fps) induces
symmetric photic driving at 5 Hz and 7 Hz (subharmonic driving at the latter frequency), which is a
normal finding.



EVENTS:


There are no clinical or electrographic events captured during this study.


HEART RATE:


A heart rate of 60 bpm is captured on a single EKG lead.


IMPRESSION:


This is an abnormal awake and asleep 1-hr EEG due to:





1. Occasional bursts of generalized irregular spike- and polyspike-and-wave activity, as detailed
above, without clear clinical correlate



CLINICAL CORRELATION:



These findings indicate the presence of generalized epileptiform potentials.




Attending Epileptologist: 

I have personally reviewed this study, and this report represents my findings and conclusions.

IMPRESSION 

This is an abnormal awake and asleep 1-hr EEG due to 




1. Occasional bursts of generalized irregular spike- and polyspike-and-wave activity, as detailed
above, without clear clinical correlate
